docs.lead_paragraph: MEMPHIS — March for Our Lives, the student-driven protest against gun violence. The Millions March against police violence. The Sacramento protest over the fatal shooting of Stephon Clark. Had he survived, the Rev. docs.abstract: The survivors of the Parkland, Fla., high school shooting have surprised many with their public activism. But they are hardly the first students to push the adult world for political change.
docs.snippet: The survivors of the Parkland, Fla., high school shooting have surprised many with their public activism. But they are hardly the first students to push the adult world for political change.
docs.lead_paragraph: Every few weeks or months, after a man armed with a high-powered weapon walks into a school or a church or a nightclub and opens fire, the national response plays out in a rote, almost performative way. The outcry lasts only a few days before guns fade back into the background noise of American politics.

headline.main: 7 Times in History When Students Turned to Activism

docs.abstract: The comedian says he doesn’t care whom he offends. But he appears to be obsessed with the topic.
docs.snippet: The comedian says he doesn’t care whom he offends. But he appears to be obsessed with the topic.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ricky Gervais, the British comedian, does not care what you say about him on Twitter. He does not care if you are offended. He does not care if you hate the latest joke he told about rape, or the Bible, or Caitlyn Jenner, or Hitler or your child’s fatal peanut allergy. And just to make sure you’re crystal clear on all of the tweets he does not remotely care about, he has built his new Netflix stand-up special, “Ricky Gervais: Humanity,” around them — these negligible tweets, the droning of gnats, several years of which he appears to have accidentally screen-grabbed and saved to his phone. (Ricky Gervais: Butterfingers!)

headline.main: The World Is Evolving and Ricky Gervais Isn’t

docs.abstract: Long before a shooting and protests in Ferguson, Mo., focused America’s attention on how the police treat black men, Los Angeles was a byword for police brutality and racism.

docs.lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — John Weber was rummaging through old boxes the other day, looking for memories, when he found a bunch of old baseball and flag football trophies. He has kept other things, too, like a neatly pressed R.O.T.C. uniform, a reminder that he once hoped to steer his son, Anthony, to the Army and away from the streets.

headline.main: Anatomy of a Los Angeles Police Shooting: A Black Teenager, a Missing Gun, Protests, Grief
headline.print_headline: In Shooting Of Teenager, City Recalls Racist Past
